        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-05-13T04:37:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "nit/observation: It seems that this type is used in three slightly different ways:\n 1. To represent triaging (expectation changes), where the Label is allowed to be any of POSITIVE/NEGATIVE/UNTRIAGED. In this case, UNTRIAGED is meaningful because it indicates a change from POSITIVE or NEGATIVE to UNTRIAGED.\n 2. To represent stored expectations, where UNTRIAGED is omitted since it\u0027s the default.\n 3. To represent baselines, where only POSITIVE is useful.\n\nIf I\u0027m understanding correctly, for #2 and #3, if somehow we wind up with Expectations where a Label is UNTRIAGED (or NEGATIVE for #3), it\u0027s not really a problem for correctness, it\u0027s just less efficient space-wise.\n\nIf that\u0027s correct, we might consider:\n - remove MergeExpectations; instead call Update.\n - add method \"TrimUntriaged\" and call it before storing/serializing Expectations (where we were previously calling MergeExpectations).\n - maybe add method \"AsBaseline\" to return a copy of Expectations with only POSITIVE labels\nThe advantage would be that it\u0027s more explicit that Expectations is allowed to have any of POSITIVE/NEGATIVE/UNTRIAGED (unless it\u0027s the result of TrimUntriaged or AsBaseline).\n\nIf that\u0027s not correct, or if the above doesn\u0027t seem like a change you want to make, it would be nice to document each use of Expectations to indicate which of POSITIVE/NEGATIVE/UNTRIAGED it might contain. Where one of those is not allowed, it would also be nice to document each mutation to indicate why the new label is among those allowed, if it\u0027s not obvious.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 10,
        "startChar": 45,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 72
      },
      "revId": "973116f41c45b75e934398ba0f2b1f358ddfc734",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
